				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Swarming<a name="6898"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">May 1 03 3:13 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Wow....I dont see how one can make it to level 58 and not know how to swarm, being proficient or not is one story, but having no clue to the point where you dont know that you use charm to swarm is just sad, lol.
<br />

<br />
Sadly, level 58 is where the exp to be gained from swarming really starts to slack off.  Even in PoD (the best place to use the 39 charm), at level 58 regular exp swarming is almost as slow as grouping in the CY there, and much less fun, tho AA exp is faster swarming somehow...least it seems that way to me.  The amount of effort that you would have to put into learning to swarm would be greater than the reward you would get at that level, which would be decent, but not great exp.
<br />

<br />
There is a higher level charm, at level 64, that can be used to good measure in PoN, but 10 mobs that hit for an average of 100 is one thing, but you go to PoN and pick up 10 mobs that hit for 200+ and you have serious trouble if you make a little mistake.
<br />

<br />
No offense, but if you honestly made it to level 58 and think that swarming involes AoE dots, it would be a death sentence to try swarming, but I will give you a brief anyway.
<br />

<br />
First, I will assume you know how to chant-kite.  Ok, now you gather 4 (4 to start, you can do much more later) mobs that are social, frost giant scouts in GD are nice to start with at level 58, just dont hurt them in any way, even to pull, just run up to them.  Now you charm one, and make it attack another, and the other 2 (or more) giants that were chasing you will turn and proceed to beat up your pet, this is a good thing.  When your pet gets low on health, make sure you have your pet targeted, and then invis somehow, and break charm, then chant-kite the old pet to death, since it is now low on health.  Now charm another of the 3 left, and repeat, then charm one of the last 2, and repeat, but break charm before EITHER of the last 2 get below 20% or so, cause you DON'T want them to run, break charm, and switch between the last to chanting each one a bit, so they both go down in health at the same rate.  The goal on the last 2 is to have them both at 1% health at the same time, so they die at the same time, so they never stop chasing you.  If you have 1 mob after you, it turns to run at 20% and you need to snare it, if you have 2 mobs, both below 20%, neither will run, if they are social.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
